        "creation_date": 1278630728,
        "answer_count": 5,
        "title": "Exploding ROOT.war",
        "body": "<p>I am copying my ROOT.war file to webapps of Tomcat 6.0 . Is there a way I can explode the file upon copying. i.e when my script copies it in the webapps .. it should explode and create ROOT directory ??<\/p>\n",
        "question_id": 3208709,
        "tags": [
            "java",
            "perl",
            "tomcat"
        ],
        "score": 2,
        "is_answered": true,
        "view_count": 2632
    },
    "question_comments": [],
    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5dda076408c2f4c8e261a3a8e7c5580c?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 42317,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 123248,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/123248/william-pietri",
                "reputation": 3683,
                "display_name": "William Pietri",
                "accept_rate": 86
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 2.5",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1278630954,
            "creation_date": 1278630954,
            "body": "<p>There are two ways that come to mind. <\/p>\n\n<p>One is that the WAR file is a jar file, so you can use the <a href=\"http://download.oracle.com/docs/cd/E17476_01/javase/1.4.2/docs/tooldocs/windows/jar.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">jar command<\/a> to expand it.<\/p>\n\n<p>The other is to use the Tomcat <a href=\"http://tomcat.apache.org/tomcat-6.0-doc/config/host.html#Automatic%20Application%20Deployment\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">autodeploy<\/a> magic. You copy the WAR file in; Tomcat notices the change, expands the WAR, and reloads it.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 3208734,
            "question_id": 3208709
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/47208ccdce184139add60179af9c3411?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 154027,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 369692,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/369692/miro-a",
                "reputation": 7993,
                "display_name": "Miro A."
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 2.5",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1278631161,
            "creation_date": 1278631161,
            "body": "<p>The Ant task unzip/unjar will also do the trick as the WAR file is JAR/ZIP<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 3208753,
            "question_id": 3208709
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/053082988d5c2da6fe500a209f8cfdd8?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 30387,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 82865,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/82865/jonathan-holloway",
                "reputation": 64000,
                "display_name": "Jonathan Holloway",
                "accept_rate": 71
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 2.5",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1278631173,
            "creation_date": 1278631173,
            "body": "<p>Simple, but you could always do:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>cp blah.jar /usr/local/tomcat/webapps &amp;&amp; unzip blah.jar\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>It assumes Unix, on windows you should be able to do something similar...<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 3208754,
            "question_id": 3208709
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/eeec80237213c91e5bab56b77ac5b8ca?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 16878,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 37213,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/37213/duffymo",
                "reputation": 309604,
                "display_name": "duffymo",
                "accept_rate": 81
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 2.5",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1278639320,
            "creation_date": 1278639320,
            "body": "<p>You should not be putting your stuff in ROOT context.  Create a war named Foo.war and let \"Foo\" be the name of your context.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 3209258,
            "question_id": 3208709
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/9ccda0b49cc974197399eae01ebd6850?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 178183,
